ndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMost slave trades were abolished during the 19th century yet there remain millions of people in slavery today, amongst them approximately 210 million children in slavery, trafficked, in debt bondage and other forms of forced labour. This groundbreaking book, drawing on experience worldwide, shows how children remain locked in slavery, the ways in which they are exploited and how they can be emancipated. Written for policy and political actors, academics and activists, it reminds us also that all are implicated in modern childhood slavery - as consumers - and need both to understand its causes, and act to stop it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aChild labor. 0aChild slaves. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Children's Studies.2bisacsh1 aAcar, Hakan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAcar, Yüksel Baykara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAliperti, Jason, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAliperti, Patricia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBales, Kevin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlagbrough, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBokhari, Farhat, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBreuil, Brenda Oude, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrookman, Bill, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuck, Trevor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCody, Claire, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCraig, Gary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabular